- [x] 14a. Create `tests/playwright.config.ts` -- webServer `npx serve out -p 4321` after `npm run build`, `baseURL: 'http://localhost:4321'`, `use: { viewport: { width: 1440, height: 900 } }`, `expect: { toHaveScreenshot: { threshold: 0.2, maxDiffPixelRatio: 0.005 } }`.
- [x] 14b. Create `tests/fixtures/1440.spec.ts` -- three tests: `toHaveScreenshot('home.png')` for `/`, `toHaveScreenshot('docs-index.png')` for `/docs`, `toHaveScreenshot('docs-aide-spec.png')` for `/docs/methodology/aide-spec`. Each test `await page.addStyleTag({ content: '*,*::before,*::after { animation-duration: 0s !important; animation-delay: 0s !important; transition-duration: 0s !important; }' })` before screenshotting -- this freezes the Typewriter, Expo float, and CLI demo into deterministic states for byte-faithful compare.
- [x] 14c. On first run, commit the generated `tests/visual/*.png` goldens. Document in README how to regenerate (`npx playwright test --update-snapshots`).

**Traces to:** intent.aide "render pixel-for-pixel against the chosen Terminal design references ... at a 1440px desktop viewport".

**Acceptance:** `npm run test:visual` passes. Diff against committed goldens is within threshold. Any unapproved visual change to hero/docs shell/docs template fails CI until reviewed.

### 15. Responsive fallback (sidebar→drawer below 768px, layout down to 375px)

Read: `coding-playbook/client/components`

- [x] 15a. Convert `DocsSidebar` from sticky-left into a Radix/lightweight drawer below the `md:` breakpoint. Below 768px, render a `<button>` in TopBar (docs variant only) with a hamburger glyph that toggles an overlay drawer containing the sidebar content. The desktop sidebar uses `hidden md:block`; the drawer uses `block md:hidden`. No new dependencies -- implement with `useState` + a transparent-overlay div.
- [x] 15b. Marketing-page 2-column grids (Hero, IntentTree) collapse to single-column below `md:` via `grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2`. Pipeline row of 6 stage buttons wraps onto 2 rows of 3 below `md:`.
- [x] 15c. Verify at 375px: no horizontal scroll on `/`, `/docs`, `/docs/methodology/aide-spec`. TopBar collapses to `docs` + hamburger at the smallest sizes.
- [x] 15d. Expo mascot sprite shrinks to 80px below `md:` and the bubble shifts to `max-width: calc(100vw - 120px)`.

**Traces to:** intent.aide "mobile viewport (375px) is best-effort: responsive down, sidebar collapses to drawer below 768px, but not a strict Lighthouse gate".

**Acceptance:** Three canonical pages open at 375px without horizontal scroll or overlapping content. Drawer toggles the sidebar in/out.

### 16. Lighthouse pass and final definition-of-done check

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo`, `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`

- [x] 16a. Run `npm run build` → `npm run preview` → open Lighthouse in Chrome at 1440px with throttling off for desktop scoring. Capture all 4 category scores. Target ≥ 95.
- [x] 16b. If any category is < 95, diagnose (common causes: unminified CSS, oversized images, missing alt text, contrast on dim text). Fix at the source -- never add workarounds. No visual regressions allowed as part of the fix.
- [x] 16c. Run the definition-of-done checklist from `design_handoff_aidemd_site/README.md` lines 244-252: (i) marketing page identical to Terminal.html at 1440px (covered by test:visual), (ii) docs index + both written doc pages identical (covered), (iii) 6 remaining doc pages rendered from real `.aide/docs/*.md` (covered -- they ARE the source), (iv) interactions work (manual pass with Playwright screenshot + click automation), (v) mobile responsive to 375px (covered in step 15), (vi) Lighthouse ≥ 95 (covered in 16a), (vii) no CLS on hero (typewriter reserves final box).
- [x] 16d. Search the built `out/` directory for the literal string "aidey" (case-insensitive). Expected: zero hits. `grep -ri aidey out/ || true` -- empty output is the pass. The only references allowed anywhere are in `design_handoff_aidemd_site/`, which is never shipped.

**Traces to:** intent.aide "scores at least 95 in all four Lighthouse categories on a 1440px desktop run", "AIDEY or AID anywhere in shipped output ... is a spec violation".

**Acceptance:** Lighthouse ≥ 95 in all 4 categories at 1440px desktop. No "aidey" in `out/`. All visual tests pass. Definition of done from handoff README is satisfied point-by-point.

## Decisions

### Why a single plan.aide instead of sub-plans

The intent.aide anticipated sub-plans for complex modules. I considered splitting into root + sub-plans for `_components/`, `docs/`, `components/Expo/`, `service/docsRegistry/`. I rejected that because (1) the project is greenfield, so there are no prerequisite modules to front-load -- every sub-plan would declare the same "Tailwind theme + palette vars + cn helper" prerequisite from step 1, which is noise; (2) the primitives (CodeBlock, Callout, DocMeta, Expo) are shared across marketing and docs, and splitting forces the architect to pre-commit to where each primitive lives before either consumer exists -- risky; (3) the implementor's cognitive load is actually lower when the whole build order lives in one file they read once. Sub-`.aide` intent files DO exist for the two most complex orchestrators (`service/docsRegistry/.aide` in step 4a, `src/components/Expo/.aide` in step 9a) because those capture contracts non-obvious from the folder tree alone. No sub-`plan.aide` files -- this plan IS the plan.

### Why Shiki over Prism

Shiki pre-renders syntax highlighting at build time into static HTML with inline color styles, which means zero runtime JS for code blocks. Prism requires a client-side library load + DOM-walk at runtime, which adds ~30KB gzipped and a layout shift on first paint when the highlight overlay applies. For a static-export Lighthouse-≥95 site with dozens of code blocks, Shiki is the objectively smaller payload. The custom theme translates the handoff accent palette verbatim into TextMate token rules.

### Why Next.js App Router over Astro

The handoff README suggested Astro as an alternative. App Router wins because (1) the intent.aide and handoff both reference Next.js 14 App Router + MDX, (2) `next/script` afterInteractive has well-understood semantics for the GTM load (GA4 fires inside the GTM container), (3) `generateStaticParams` + `output: 'export'` produces the same static artifact as Astro with less tooling divergence, (4) the team's existing muscle memory is Next. No behavioral advantage to Astro here.

### Why CSS variables + Tailwind v4 @theme tokens instead of per-component CSS

The playbook's "No CSS-in-JS or CSS Modules" anti-pattern is a hard rule. Tailwind v4's `@theme` block maps CSS variables to Tailwind utility tokens; every handoff palette hex becomes both a CSS variable (`var(--color-accent)`) AND a utility class (`bg-accent`, `text-accent`). Component-specific values that don't fit the design-system scale are expressed as Tailwind arbitrary values (e.g. `p-[14px_16px]`, `grid-cols-[280px_1fr]`). No .module.css files. No styled-components. No inline `style={{}}` when a Tailwind utility works. Per the `feedback_globals_css_scope_resolution` memo, globals.css holds exactly: @theme tokens, :root var aliases, @keyframes, ::selection, :focus-visible, prefers-reduced-motion. That's it.

### Why a build-time filesystem walk instead of a static manifest

intent.aide lists "a hardcoded list of doc pages anywhere in the codebase" as an undesired outcome. A manifest would be a hardcoded list. The filesystem walk is the structural guarantee against drift -- adding a .md file under any of the 4 content roots automatically produces a route. Trade-off: slightly slower build (4 `readdir` calls plus one `git log` per file). At 33 files the build-time cost is negligible (< 100ms total). The cache in `resolveCommitHash` guarantees we shell out to git exactly once per file per build.

### Handoff mascot pose mapping (load-bearing, user-spec-breaking risk flagged)

intent.aide demands four public/ files: `expo-teach.png`, `expo-think.png`, `expo-wave.png`, `expo-point.png`. The handoff `design_handoff_aidemd_site/prototypes/assets/` ships only THREE pose crops: `aidey-teach.png`, `aidey-read.png`, `aidey-wave.png` (plus `aidey-character-sheet.png` which is a design-process artifact, not a shipable sprite). I'm mapping as follows: teach → expo-teach.png, read → expo-think.png (the "read" pose IS thinking body-language), wave → expo-wave.png, teach (reused) → expo-point.png. This is a deliberate 3-asset → 4-pose expansion; the alternative is to crop a new "point" pose from the character-sheet PNG, which is out of scope for v1 and would be a design decision rather than an implementation decision. Flag: if the user prefers a dedicated point pose, commission one and re-run step 3 to replace the file.

### Why IntersectionObserver for Expo tips instead of scroll-Y math

intent.aide explicitly calls for IntersectionObserver. IO is cheaper than scroll listeners (browser-coordinated, not rAF-driven), and the threshold=0.4 + rootMargin -30%/-30% combination gives the intuitive "the section I'm looking at" semantics without needing to hand-tune pixel offsets. The context provider pattern (ExpoTipContext) avoids prop-drilling and satisfies the "no state management libraries" anti-pattern -- React Context is the escape hatch for cross-cutting state that the playbook allows.

### Why per-route alternates.canonical AND a client CanonicalTag

Static export supports `alternates.canonical` in `generateMetadata` for known routes, and that's preferred. But the root layout's client `CanonicalTag` remains as a belt-and-suspenders fallback for any route that forgets to set metadata (and for error routes where Next.js may not run generateMetadata). If the per-route metadata is correct, CanonicalTag's useEffect is a no-op (it'll set the same href). No duplicate tags -- the client updates the existing tag in place.

### Why `trailingSlash: true` in next.config.mjs

GitHub Pages serves directories as `/foo/index.html`. Without trailingSlash, Next.js static export outputs `/docs/methodology/aide-spec.html` which Pages happily serves at `/docs/methodology/aide-spec` -- but internal links using `<Link href="/docs/...">` would 404 in preview environments that don't strip `.html`. trailingSlash ensures every route is `/docs/methodology/aide-spec/index.html`, which Pages, `serve`, and any static host handles identically.

### Why the 6-item nav maps `docs`→`/docs`, `commands/agents/skills`→`/docs/<section>`

intent.aide says: "Expose four separate docs sections as four separate top-level nav entries." The nav items are visible labels; the URL structure is orthogonal. Keeping all docs under `/docs/*` preserves one docs layout, one sidebar, one template, one filesystem-walk registry. The four labels point to the four section roots within /docs -- and **each of those URLs resolves to a real section-index page** (built by `/docs/[section]/page.tsx`, step 10n), not just a URL pattern that happens to be valid. Clicking `agents` lands on `/docs/agents/`, which renders an index of the 9 agent pages; clicking `commands` lands on `/docs/commands/`, which renders the 13 command pages; and so on. The four labels are first-class routes with their own H1, lede, and DocsIndexCard list -- this collapses to the same experience as if each were a top-level route, without duplicating layout components.

### Why section-index pages at `/docs/<section>/`

Progressive disclosure: a user clicking `agents` in the nav has a strong implicit signal "show me what agents exist". The alternatives are (a) hash-anchor scrolling on the global `/docs/` index page, which works visually but breaks deep-linking and back-button semantics; (b) collapsing all 4 nav links to `/docs/` and letting the user scroll-find, which fails the "four separate top-level nav entries" intent; (c) creating a real index page per section, which is what we do. The cost is one new page route (`[section]/page.tsx`) -- but it reuses every primitive (Breadcrumb, DocsIndexCard, DocsFooter) so there is no new visual vocabulary. The active-row rule on DocsSidebar becomes "pathname starts with the route's prefix" instead of strict equality (so `/docs/agents/` highlights every row in the agents CategoryBlock as part of the active section, even though no specific row's `current` matches). Same for ActiveAwareTopBar: prefix-based, not equality-based. This means a user at `/docs/agents/aide-architect/` and a user at `/docs/agents/` both see the `agents` nav highlighted -- the active state is "you're inside the agents section", not "you're on this exact URL".

### Expo tip copy: 5 verbatim from handoff, 5 newly authored

The 5 tips in `aidey.jsx` `AIDEY_TIPS_DEFAULT` are brand-approved copy from the handoff. Re-drafting them would be re-deciding settled brand voice; they get ported verbatim with a single substitution `s/AIDEY/Expo/g` (intent.aide demands the mascot be renamed to Expo). The 5 source tips happen to map naturally to 5 of the 10 SectionIds (`hero`, `threeLayerModel`, `intentTree`, `vaultBrain`, `quickstart`); the remaining 5 sections (`pipeline`, `cliDemo`, `comparison`, `footer`, `docs`) need new tips. Those are authored fresh in step 2i, matching the source tone exactly: all-lowercase titles, second person, 1-2 sentences, framework=AIDE / mascot=Expo kept distinct, no "AIDEY" or abandoned interim "AID" anywhere. **Pose rename `read → think`:** the source tip for `vaultBrain` uses pose `'read'`. But the public/ asset filename is `expo-think.png` (step 3b copies `aidey-read.png → expo-think.png`), and the `ExpoPose` type in `src/types/expo.ts` enumerates only `'teach'|'think'|'wave'|'point'`. So the data file MUST encode the `vaultBrain` tip's pose as `'think'`, not `'read'`. The handoff's "read" pose IS reading-as-thinking body language, so the rename is semantic-preserving, not destructive. Documented inline in the data file's JSDoc.

### Comparison rows: port verbatim from variant-editorial.jsx, do NOT redraft

The OpenSpec vs AIDE comparison rows in `variant-editorial.jsx` `ComparisonTable` (lines 249-257) are brand-approved copy. The visual *direction* of variant-editorial was rejected in favor of variant-terminal, but the table's *data* survived the rejection -- it's the same set of comparable claims either way. Re-drafting would re-decide settled brand copy. Step 2h ports all 7 rows verbatim, with source verification required (the implementor opens variant-editorial.jsx and confirms the rows match before encoding -- if there's a discrepancy, they flag back rather than silently using the user-provided text). Field-name change `topic → dimension`: the brand-approved column header is "Dimension", so the field name follows. Column-order change in step 8d: the brand-approved column order is `Dimension | AIDE | OpenSpec` (AIDE in the middle), and the middle column gets weight-500 + solid foreground while the outer columns get 55% opacity dim. The middle-column emphasis is the table's primary visual rhetoric -- it answers "which framework is this page about" without text -- so getting the column order right is load-bearing.

### Why raw HTML + rehype instead of @mdx-js/react or @next/mdx

The docs content is plain markdown (`.md`, not `.mdx`), sourced from two independent tool ecosystems (the AIDE canonical docs and the Claude Code skills/commands). Introducing MDX would require re-authoring the content with React component imports -- which defeats the "render directly from this repo's filesystem" guarantee in intent.aide. Unified + rehype gives us the HTML we need with Shiki integration. Callouts are handled via a small rehype plugin that converts GitHub-flavored `> [!NOTE] ... > body` blockquotes into `<div class="callout callout-note">` before render; the Callout component's styling applies via a `.callout-note` utility in globals.css OR by replacing the div server-side with `<Callout kind="note">` via rehype-react. Pick rehype-react for type safety in step 10k -- if it proves painful, fall back to class-based CSS targeting. Decision noted in plan step 10k.

### Why Playwright over DOM-snapshot tests for pixel-fidelity

The intent.aide outcome is rendered output matching the JSX prototypes "pixel-for-pixel at 1440px". DOM snapshots can catch structural drift but cannot catch color drift, spacing drift, font-weight drift, or kerning differences. Playwright `toHaveScreenshot` at a fixed viewport is the only test that actually verifies rendered pixels. The 0.2 threshold + 0.005 maxDiffPixelRatio gives a ~0.5% pixel tolerance which is generous enough to survive font-rasterization variance across Playwright versions but tight enough to catch a palette swap or a 2px spacing miss. Playwright is a dev-dep; browsers install only in CI. Per the playbook, component tests are "most brittle, least valuable" -- visual regression is not component tests, it's acceptance tests, and those are load-bearing here.

### Why the spacing scale lives in globals.css `@theme` tokens

The scale is 4/8/12/14/16/18/20/24/28/32/40/44/60/64/80. Tailwind's default scale (`p-1 = 4px, p-2 = 8px`) covers most but not all (e.g., `14px, 18px, 44px, 60px` are not Tailwind defaults). Defining `--spacing-14: 14px` etc. in @theme gives utility classes like `p-14` that map to the exact custom values. The alternative -- arbitrary values like `p-[14px]` everywhere -- works but visually clutters JSX. Defining the scale once in @theme keeps the JSX readable AND enforces "no ad-hoc spacing values" (any `p-[13px]` in review is an obvious spec violation).

### Why `design_handoff_aidemd_site/` stays in the repo (and out of public/)

The handoff directory is the visual source of truth for every plan step. Developers diff against it during implementation. Deleting it after the build would leave future maintainers without the reference. Keeping it in the repo is correct; shipping it to public/ would be a spec violation (scaffolding in production). next.config.mjs + Next's static asset resolver only serves files from `public/` -- the handoff directory stays on disk, invisible to the built site. No action needed; just never copy out of it into public/ except via step 3.

### Scope note on step 15 (mobile responsive)

The intent.aide is explicit that mobile is "best-effort, not strict" and not a Lighthouse gate. Step 15 delivers the "sidebar→drawer below 768px" and "usable at 375px" requirements but does NOT attempt parity with the desktop visual density at smaller sizes. Pixel-fidelity applies at 1440px only; below 768px, the layout is responsive/functional but not pixel-compared. The visual regression suite (step 14) only screenshots at 1440px.
